  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT361-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">varaivu malintavaḻit tōḻi “naṉkāṟṟiṉāy” eṉṟāṭkuk kiḻatti colliyatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by HER to the one, who said “you have well had
          the strength”, [namely] the confidante, when she rejoiced over the [coming] marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT361">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> amma vāḻi tōḻi yaṉṉaik</l>
          <l> kuyarnilai yulakamuñ ciṟitā lavarmalai</l>
          <l> mālaip peyta maṇaṅkama ḻuntiyoṭu</l>
          <l> kālai vanta kāntaṇ muḻumutaṉ</l>
          <l> mellilai kuḻaiya muyaṅkalu</l>
          <l> milluyttu naṭutaluṅ kaṭiyā tōḷē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Alas, oh friend, for mother</l>
          <l>indeed <note place="foot"> The  <term xml:lang="ta"> -ē </term> here follows upon the   <term xml:lang="ta"> -āl</term> in a long postposition (to be connected with the beginning of the poem). </note> also the upper <note place="foot"> Does  <term xml:lang="ta"> uyarnilai ulakam </term> refer to the world of the gods (cf. <term xml:lang="ta"> puttēḷ nāṭu </term> in KT 101.2)?  </note> world would be a small [return],</l>
      <l>she who did not prevent [me from] setting up  <note place="foot"> naṭutal: what is this supposed to mean? To plant? Or to put into a vase?   </note>   in the house</l>
      <l rend="indent">and embracing, softly <note place="foot">
        <term xml:lang="ta"> kuḻaiya</term> presumably is to be understood as an adverbial infinitive. T.V.G. reads "so that it (i.e. the plant) becomes soft (i.e. looses shape)", but this does not fit the context so well.</note> , the tender leaves</l>
    <l rend="indent">of the whole stem of the Malabar lily, come in the morning</l>
    <l rend="indent2">with the river, fragrant with the scent <note place="foot">The choice of <term xml:lang="ta">  maṇam </term>, which does not only mean "fragrance" but also "union" (and is mostly used in the latter sense), is certainly not by chance. </note>  rained in the evening</l>
  <l rend="indent6">from his mountain.</l>


</lg>
</div>
